\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Notes are Staff Objects.  Notes may range in duration from 128th note to double breve.  Notes may appear in four styles: Modern, Old Book, diamond head, and cross head.  Attributes of a note, such as dots, accidentals, ledger lines, and stem length and direction are automatically calculated based on the context in which a note appears. Notes may be chords having up to sixteen noteheads (see \b Chord Tool\b0 ).\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 The selection area of a note lies within any notehead.  If one of the noteheads is selected, the entire note is selected, and most commands apply to the entire note, but some commands apply to the selected notehead itself. \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 As for any staff object, notes may have text underlay associated with them (see \b Verses\b0 ).\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 As for any voiced object, Notes may have a voice number associated with them, which is used when formatting and playback of multi-voice works (see \b Voices\b0 ).  Each note may have  a part (see \b Parts\b0 ) associated with it.  During playback, a note will produce a sound associated with an instrument specified by the part.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\keepn\fi0\sb240\sa80\li0\ri0\f1\fs32\b1\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 To make a note \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 There are several methods for making notes.  Some of these are as follows:\par
\pard\tx360\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi-230\sb80\sa0\li360\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 ·	 Select the Note Tool.  Click on a staff to place the note where the pointer is.\par
\pard\tx360\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi-230\sb80\sa0\li360\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 ·	 Enter notes via a MIDI input device (see \b Playback\b0 ).\par
\pard\tx360\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi-230\sb80\sa0\li360\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 ·	 Select one or more notes.  Press Copy (Command-c).  Then press Paste (Command-v).  The new copies will be placed immediately to the left of the originals and selected.\par
\pard\tx360\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi-230\sb80\sa0\li360\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 ·	 Select one or more notes.  Press Copy (Command-c).  Then press the \b Paste Tool\b0 .  Now each time the mouse is clicked, a copy of the original selection will be placed at the mouse location and selected.  Press the Arrow Tool (or the \fs24\f1\b0\i0 E\f1 sc\f0  key) to cancel the Paste Tool.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\keepn\fi0\sb240\sa80\li0\ri0\f1\fs32\b1\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Note placement \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 As for any staff object, notes are automatically placed when the system is adjusted (see \b Adjustment\b0 ).  To otherwise move a note, select the note and hold the mouse button down to drag the note to a desired location.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 To move noteheads of a chord independently, click on the desired notehead and ALT-drag it to the desired staff position.  See the \b Chord Tool\b0  for more information on chords.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\keepn\fi0\sb240\sa80\li0\ri0\f1\fs32\b1\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 The Note Inspector  \par
