\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\ql\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 When a note is selected, its attributes will be displayed by the inspector.  Any attribute can be changed, and the changes will take effect when the \fs24\f1\b0\i0 S\f1 ET\f0  button is pressed.  If multiple notes are in a selection, the note inspector will display those attributes that are identical across the selection.  For non-identical attributes, the note inspector will indicate a multiple selection in a way depending on what kind of control displays the attribute.  For example, a matrix of buttons shows no selection; a popup menu reads \fs24\f1\b0\i0 m\f1 ultiple selection\f0 , a text box is empty, and a switch shows a horizontal line.  A change to an attribute indicating multiple selection will take effect on all selected notes when \fs24\f1\b0\i0 S\f1 ET\f0  is pressed.  If \fs24\f1\b0\i0 S\f1 ET\f0  is pressed, no action is taken for attributes which remain indicating a multiple selection.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0\fs24\f1\b0\i0 D\f1 uration\f0 :  Specifies the duration of the note.  This attribute may also be modified with a keyboard equivalent.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0\fs24\f1\b0\i0 D\f1 ots\f0 :  Specified the number of dots associated with the duration of the note.  The blank button means no dots.  Single dots may be added or deleted with a keyboard equivalent.  The vertical double dot is a notation used in early music.  If a note of duration \i n\i0  is has a vertical double-dot, the full duration is: \i n\i0  + (5\i n \i0 / 4).  This is by contrast to an ordinary double-dot, for which the total duration is  \i n \i0 + (3\i n\i0  / 4).\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0\fs24\f1\b0\i0 A\f1 ccidental\f0 :  Specifies the accidental associated with the note.  The blank button means no accidental.  This attribute may also be modified with a keyboard equivalent.  Accidentals are placed in a conventional position before the note head, and are formatted automatically depending on the noteheads of the chord and the other accidentals.  For small editorial accidentals above or below the note, use Punctuation instead (see \b Punctuation Tool\b0 ).  For the accidentals used in figured bass notation, use the special facility for figured bass notation instead (see \b Figured Bass\b0 ).\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0\fs24\f1\b0\i0 E\f1 ditorial\f0 :  Specifies the type of editorial brackets around the accidental.  To place editorial brackets around the entire note or a significant part of it, use an Enclosure (see \b Enclosure Tool\b0 ).\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0\fs24\f1\b0\i0 S\f1 tem Direction\f0 :  Shows the direction of the stem.  Stem direction is automatically calculated when the note is moved or modified.  If you wish to override the automatic setting of stem direction,  press the desired stem direction button and check the \fs24\f1\b0\i0 F\f1 ixed\f0  box.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0\fs24\f1\b0\i0 F\f1 ixed\f0 : Stem direction will not change from that shown in the \fs24\f1\b0\i0 S\f1 tem Direction\f0  indicator, regardless of the note's position on the staff.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0\fs24\f1\b0\i0 S\f1 temless\f0 :  If checked, no stem is printed.  This is used mainly for modern chant notation (see \b Chant Notation\b0 ).\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0\fs24\f1\b0\i0 L\f1 ocked\f0 :  If checked, the note will remain attached to its staff no matter how far away it is dragged with the mouse.  If not checked, a note is unlocked: it will attach itself to the nearest staff when it is dragged.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0\fs24\f1\b0\i0 T\f1 ight\f0 :  Specifies that the note is to be followed by less than the normal amount of spacing.  This is not generally useful, as most need for non-standard spacing (\i e.g.\i0  sesquialtera, coloured notation) are met by changing the proportionality of the governing time signature (see \b Time Signature\b0 ).\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0\fs24\f1\b0\i0 S\f1 tyle\f0 :  Specifies the graphic style of the note.  The choices are (reading from left to right):  Modern, Old Book, Old Book Coloured (the note head has reverse shading); diamond head (used for harmonics), and cross head (used for spoken notes).\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0\fs24\f1\b0\i0 T\f1 iming\f0 : The choices are (reading from left to right):  normal, grace, timed-back.  Grace timing is used for grace notes (see the \fs24\f1\b0\i0 G\f1 race\f0\b\b  \b0\b0 Command).  Timed-back is used in late entry situations where it is convenient to time notes back from the barline at the end of the measure.  For explanation of use see index entries under `multiple voice notation' and `late entry'.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0\fs24\f1\b0\i0 P\f1 art/Instrument\f0 :  Specifies the part, or alternatively, an instrument for this note. The lower popup menu displays one of the following:  \fs24\f1\b0\i0 D\f1 efined by Staff's Part\f0 , \fs24\f1\b0\i0 D\f1 efined by Note's Part\f0 , or \fs24\f1\b0\i0 D\f1 efined by this note\f0 . For explanation of use see \b Parts\b0  and \b Instruments\b0 . When overriding the part assignment on a note-by-note basis using the note inspector, it is necessary to change the lower popup menu \i first\i0 , then the upper popup menu.  This is because the lower popup menu can cause the upper menu to display different menus depending on what is selected.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0\fs24\f1\b0\i0 V\f1 oice\f0 :  Specifies the voice number of this note.  The default is voice 0.  For explanation of use see index entries under `multiple voice notation'.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0\fs24\f1\b0\i0 V\f1 erses Above\f0 :  Specifies how many of the verses of this note are to be displayed above the staff.  For a value of n, the first n verses are displayed above the staff; the remaining verses are displayed below the staff.  For explanation of use see index entries under `verses'.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0\fs24\f1\b0\i0 T\f1 OOL\f0 :  Updates the Note Tools to use the specified options when new notes are created using the Tool Palette.  All the options except duration may be specified for setting the Note Tool.  \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0\fs24\f1\b0\i0 S\f1 ET\f0 :  The specified options take effect on the selected note or notes.\par
